## User Story 2

### Background & Backstory

Marisol Dela Cruz is a 68 year old retired nurse who immigrated from the Philippines in her 20s and now lives with her adult daughter's family in Chula Vista. She raised three kids, worked 12 hour hospital shifts for over four decades, and now spends her days helping with the grandchildren, cooking, and watching K-dramas on her laptop in the evenings. A neighbor introduced her to slot games about two years ago as a way to relax before bed, and it stuck. She's not a gambler in any serious sense. She plays with fake coins, never spends real money, and doesn't understand the detailed mechanics. She just likes the cheerful sounds, the spinning reels, and the little burst of excitement when something lines up.

### Goals

- Relax and decompress after a long day without having to think hard
- Experience small, pleasant bursts of excitement from wins
- Never feel confused, overwhelmed, or frustrated by the interface
- Pick up and put down the game easily

### Motivations

- The game is soothing when it's simple and visually calm
- Small wins feel like little gifts at the end of a long day
- The repetitive, low-stakes nature is the point. She doesn't want depth, she just wants comfort
- It reminds her of the coin-pusher machines she played with her kids at the mall

### Why She's Playing

Marisol is in bed at 10pm with her laptop propped on a pillow, grandkids asleep down the hall. The room is dim. She has her reading glasses on. She'll play for 20–30 minutes before she falls asleep, clicking the spin button at a relaxed pace, half-watching a K-drama recap video in the other tab.

### Behavior

- Clicks slowly, doesn't rush, doesn't use auto-spin
- Never explores settings or reads the paytable
- Quits immediately if something confuses her or looks broken
- Gravitates toward games that feel familiar. She replays the same one rather than trying new ones
- Reacts positively to gentle sounds and warm colors; negatively to flashing or jarring effects

### Marisol's Story

As a casual elderly player who uses a laptop and just wants simple, relaxing entertainment, I want to immediately and clearly understand whether I won or lost after each spin, using large readable text and calm visuals, so that I can enjoy the game without confusion, eye strain, or overstimulation before bed.

### Marisol's Wishlist

- Win/loss result is displayed in large, high-contrast text front and center after every spin
- Win messages use warm, positive colors; loss messages are neutral and non-alarming
- Animations are present but soft. No strobing, no aggressive flashing, no full-screen screen shakes
- Font across the entire UI defaults to a clean, large sans-serif
